atrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish: topographic name from <i>aldea</i> ‘village’, a word of Arabic origin."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Andrew de Andea was born in 1122, in Cardigan, Cardiganshire, Wales. He married Lleucu ferch Gwaithfoed of Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1153, in Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1122–1153":"1122–1153","1124–Female":"1124–Surnud","1145–1175":"1145–1175","Abt 1145":"umbes 1145","1124":"1124","1145":"1145","1122":"1122","1153":"1153","1175":"1175","Cardigan, Ceredigion, Wales":"Cardigan, Cardiganshire, Wales","Powys Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1122–1153":"1122–1153","1124–Female":"1124–Kuollut","1145–1175":"1145–1175","Abt 1145":"noin 1145","1124":"1124","1145":"1145","1122":"1122","1153":"1153","1175":"1175","Cardigan, Ceredigion, Wales":"Cardigan, Cardiganshire, Wales","Powys Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Castle, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Welshpool, Mont